Certainly! Let's create an interesting interactive visualization using JavaScript and HTML5 canvas. We'll build a simple interactive bar chart that changes its appearance when you hover over it.

Here’s a step-by-step guide to creating this visualization:

1. **HTML Structure**: Set up the basic HTML structure.
2. **CSS Styling**: Add some basic styling to make the chart look nice.
3. **JavaScript Logic**: Write the JavaScript code to draw the bar chart and handle interactions.

### Step 1: HTML Structure

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Bar Chart</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>
    <canvas id="barChart"></canvas>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Step 2: CSS Styling

```css
/* styles.css */
body {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
    height: 100vh;
    margin: 0;
    background-color: #f0f0f0;
}

canvas {
    border: 1px solid black;
}
```

### Step 3: JavaScript Logic

```javascript
// script.js
const canvas = document.getElementById('barChart');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');

canvas.width = window.innerWidth * 0.8;
canvas.height = window.innerHeight * 0.6;

const data = [30, 75, 45, 90, 60, 85, 55]; // Sample data for the bars
const barWidth = 40;
const barSpacing = 10;
const maxValue = Math.max(...data);
const barHeightScale = canvas.height / maxValue;

function drawBar(index, value) {
    const x = index * (barWidth + barSpacing);
    const y = canvas.height - (value * barHeightScale);

    ctx.fillStyle = 'steelblue';
    ctx.fillRect(x, y, barWidth, value * barHeightScale);

    ctx.strokeStyle = 'black';
    ctx.strokeRect(x, y, barWidth, value * barHeightScale);

    ctx.fillStyle = 'white';
    ctx.fillText(`${value}`, x + barWidth / 2, y + 10, barWidth);
}

function draw() {
    ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);

    data.forEach((value, index) => {
        drawBar(index, value);
    });
}

function handleMouseOver(event) {
    const rect = canvas.getBoundingClientRect();
    const mouseX = event.clientX - rect.left;
    const mouseY = event.clientY - rect.top;

    for (let i = 0; i < data.length; i++) {
        const x = i * (barWidth + barSpacing);
        const y = canvas.height - (data[i] * barHeightScale);

        if (mouseX > x && mouseX < x + barWidth && mouseY > y && mouseY < canvas.height) {
            ctx.fillStyle = 'red';
            ctx.fillRect(x, y, barWidth, data[i] * barHeightScale);
            ctx.fillStyle = 'white';
            ctx.fillText(`${data[i]}`, x + barWidth / 2, y + 10, barWidth);
            break;
        }
    }
}

canvas.addEventListener('mousemove', handleMouseOver);

draw();
```

### Explanation:

1. **HTML**: Sets up the canvas element where the chart will be drawn.
2. **CSS**: Centers the canvas on the screen and adds a simple border.
3. **JavaScript**:
   - Defines the canvas dimensions based on the viewport size.
   - Creates sample data for the bar chart.
   - `drawBar` function draws each bar with appropriate height and color.
   - `draw` function clears the canvas and redraws all bars.
   - `handleMouseOver` function highlights the bar under the mouse cursor by changing its color and text color.

This example provides a simple yet interactive bar chart. You can further enhance it by adding more features like tooltips, animations, or dynamic data updates.

